          "body": "Once forgiveness is grasped (v.4), the psalmist's posture changes. He no longer flails in the depths; he *waits*. The Hebrew verbs *qavah* and *yachal* both mean to wait expectantly, but *qavah* carries the sense of a cord stretched tight — taut, alert, under tension. The psalmist's whole *nephesh* (the self in its totality) is engaged. And the object of waiting is not vague — *in His word do I hope* (v.5). Hope is anchored on God's *davar*, His revealed promises, not on circumstantial signs. Then comes the image that has captured every careful reader: *My soul waits for the Lord more than the watchmen for the morning; indeed, more than the watchmen for the morning.* The third-watch sentry on Jerusalem's walls strained through the long pre-dawn hours, knowing the morning would come but unable to hasten it. The watchman does not produce the dawn; he awaits it. The repetition intensifies the comparison — the psalmist's waiting *exceeds* even that. There is no spiritual life without this posture."
